    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-03-06T04:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-03-06T04:00:00-05:00" n="175"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d175">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">861.002/190: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Steinhardt</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-03-06T12:00:00+03:00"
                            >March 6, 1940—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received March 6—10:30 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>246. My telegram No. 228, March 1, 4 p.m. The German Ambassador<note n="16"
                        xml:id="d175fn16">Friedrich Werner, Count von der Schulenburg.</note> told
                    me last night in strict confidence that Potemkin’s dismissal had its origin in
                    part in the failure to prevent the Anglo-French-Turkish alliance<note n="17"
                        xml:id="d175fn17">Treaty of Mutual Assistance signed at Ankara on October
                        19, 1939; for text, see League of Nations Treaty Series, vol. <hi
                            rend="smallcaps">cc</hi>, p. 167.</note> and that Stalin<note n="18"
                        xml:id="d175fn18">Iosif Vissarionovich Stalin, Secretary General of the
                        Central Committee of the Ail-Union Communist Party (Bolsheviks); member of
                        the Politburo and Orgburo of the Party, etc.</note> and Molotov had held <pb
                        facs="0199" n="187" xml:id="pg_187"/> Potemkin responsible for the
                    reorientation of Turkish policy away from the Soviet Union. He also said that in
                    his opinion either Sobolev<note n="19" xml:id="d175fn19">Arkady Alexandrovich
                        Sobolev.</note> who is at present Secretary General of the Foreign Office,
                    or Lozovski<note n="20" xml:id="d175fn20">Solomon Abramovich Lozovsky, an
                        alternate member of the Executive Committee of the Third (Communist)
                        International, elected at the VII Congress in 1935; appointed an Assistant
                        People’s Commissar for Foreign Affairs of the Soviet Union on June 9,
                        1939.</note> would probably succeed Potemkin. Repeated to Ankara.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Steinhardt</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
